Unkown Pleasures Pyrenees Fly-by!

(a brief explanation can be found below, but beware!: clicking Start may place quite a lot of stress on your memory and processor (and your battery, when played on a mobile device))


Start!

Well, this is a weird construction inspired by Joy Division's Unkown Pleasures iconic album cover, plus a certain sci-fi movie I vaguelyremember as having watched as a kid and my fondness for mountains (and particularly the Pyrenees).

The idea was assembling a scene in three.js with DEM data for the Pyrenees range. Getting started with three.js and working out how to assemble a terrain-like mesh as slices took only a few hours. The main problem was therefore getting DEM data and feeding it into three.js. I was expecting the handling or geographic data to be a pain: for starters I had never have the need to deal with that before, and I also happen to be kind of rusty on Math. I didn't even know how DEM data is usually delivered, but I soon found out that it's usually handed in GeoTIFF format. Never heard of that before, but it's truly a brilliant idea. Simply put: maps are rendered as TIFF images (which is quite a straightforward choice), with pixel values showing any magnitude you may need (in DEM maps the pixel value is -you guess- the terrain elevation at that point); GeoTIFF maps also include metadata tags needed to evaluate the data payload as well as georeferencing the image to the real-world area mapped. The great thing about the GeoTIFF format is that any imaging software with TIFF support will at least be able to show a GeoTIFF map, as it is fully TIFF-compatible (GeoTIFF-specific tags will simply be ignored when unsupported); therefore you don't need specific software if you merely want to take a look at a GeoTIFF map and do some basic operations with it. It also benefits from the lossless compression builtin in the TIFF format.

So I got a DEM map for our area of interest from Copernicus' Land Monitoring Service with 25 meter/pixel resolution, which would be bad for a printed hiking map but fine enough for our purposes. There was still the problem of getting elevation data for a mesh of selected points in it. But I was pleased to find that particularly easy by means of GDAL , a set of tools for handling of raster and vector geospatial data: you just need to feed a command (gdallocationinfo) with the map file and a pair or (longitude, latitude) coordinates to get the related magnitude (elevation, in our case); no need to mess with complicated geographic operations, TIFF data structures, etc. It works like a charm, it can't be any simpler. It was only left to build a grid of (long, lat) coordinates (for our area of interest, a rectangle would do just fine), feed it into gdallocationinfo and assemble the resulting data as Javascript arrays. Nothing too hard to achieve with some Bash magic and a bit of spreadsheet pre/postprocessing.

The result is what an explorer from an alien civilization in their late '70s would watch on its UFO dashboard when flying over the area. Satisfied about it. I've had tons of fun, too.

PS. Pretty much grateful to three.js,Niles Ritter (deviser of the GeoTIFF standard), Copernicus, GDAL, Bash, Linux, LibreOffice and everyone putting ideas and open software on the Internet for the benefit of Mankind!

PS2, Just after I had got a first working version, I found that some people had similar ideas before.

PS3. And finally came to know that that old sci-fi movie is my much-admired-and-many-times-watched Alien. Fun fact: Alien and Unknown Pleasures were released almost simultaneously, in the spring or 1979.
